

Here's a curated list of **10 high-frequency medium-level problems** that cover the most important algorithmic patterns. If you become comfortable with these, you'll have a solid foundation for most backend online coding assessments.

|  # | Problem                                        | Main Pattern                               |
| -: | ---------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
|  1 | Longest Consecutive Sequence                   | **Hash Set**                               |
|  2 | Top K Frequent Elements                        | **Bucket Sort / Hash Map**                 |
|  3 | Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters | **Sliding Window**                         |
|  4 | Container With Most Water                      | **Two Pointers**                           |
|  5 | Koko Eating Bananas                            | **Binary Search on Answer**                |
|  6 | Number of Islands                              | **Graph Traversal (DFS/BFS)**              |
|  7 | Clone Graph                                    | **Graph Traversal + Hash Map**             |
|  8 | Binary Tree Level Order Traversal              | **Tree Traversal (BFS)**                   |
|  9 | Validate Binary Search Tree                    | **Binary Tree (DFS / In-order Traversal)** |
| 10 | Merge Intervals                                | **Sorting + Greedy**                       |

## Why these?

They cover the patterns that appear repeatedly across platforms like LeetCode, HackerRank, CodeSignal, Codility, and many company-specific online assessments:

* ✅ Hash Set
* ✅ Hash Map
* ✅ Bucket Sort
* ✅ Sliding Window
* ✅ Two Pointers
* ✅ Binary Search
* ✅ DFS
* ✅ BFS
* ✅ Trees
* ✅ Graphs
* ✅ Sorting
* ✅ Greedy

---

## After these 10

I recommend moving on to another set of 10 that introduces additional core patterns:

| Problem                              | Pattern               |
| ------------------------------------ | --------------------- |
| Product of Array Except Self         | Prefix Sum            |
| Daily Temperatures                   | Monotonic Stack       |
| Min Stack                            | Stack Design          |
| Evaluate Reverse Polish Notation     | Stack                 |
| Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array | Binary Search         |
| Search in Rotated Sorted Array       | Binary Search         |
| Course Schedule                      | Topological Sort      |
| Pacific Atlantic Water Flow          | DFS                   |
| Rotting Oranges                      | Multi-source BFS      |
| Kth Largest Element in an Array      | Heap (Priority Queue) |

By the end of these **20 problems**, you'll have practiced nearly all of the fundamental algorithmic patterns that show up in backend coding interviews. From there, you can focus on more advanced topics like Dynamic Programming, Tries, Union-Find, and advanced graph algorithms as needed.





